We'd have a society that would provide for those of us who need support, instead of using marginalized communities as a fucking "but look at how bad they have it" salve and then doing fuck-all to support them. Ppl really don't get how capitalism warps every facet of our lives.

"CHILDREN NEED TO BE IN SCHOOL!"
"But COVID could kill them! Or they could spread it to others!"
"Death is inevitable, oh well!" 

Like constantly swinging back and forth between two shitty fucking things and the rich just get richer. We need to remove capitalism from death.

It's true- death cannot be prevented forever. It comes for all of us, no matter what we do. But too many ppl get rich off two ideas- that both humans can purchase immortality and their lives are worth less than capital. So we drain ourselves trying to avoid the realities of death

We can't soothe our dysregulated systems any longer by saying, "well at least I don't have it as bad as they do" bc this pandemic, fueled by capitalism, is swiftly and cruelly making trauma equals out of us. The belief that your life is easier/safer is gone. COVID DGAF.

My parents, like so many other people, were conditioned to excuse and explain away upsetting shit because acknowledging and dealing with the discomfort and pain was too much, too unbearable. But it only goes so far. It's not sustainable, and Covid is proving that.

My parents had moved back to the BX at that point so I called them to come pick me up. As I'm crying in the back of their car my father tells me to just stop, bc, and I shit you not, "children have cancer!" I yelled, "CAN I GET TEN FUCKING MINUTES TO BE UPSET?"

In 2016, I was robbed at my MNR stop. I was finishing a train beer after work, listening to music, when I was "stabbed"- it was a piece of wood- I grabbed the wood out of their hand and screamed "DID YOU FUCKING STAB ME?!". They punched me in the head, took my phone and took off.

I know in some ways it was a survival technique- like in my family, it was, "it could be worse, we could still be in Ireland" and that's a whole OTHER fucking thread bc colonization is to blame there- but it no longer serves that purpose. It only bolsters capitalism.

ALSO, we can no longer practice the harmful and useless "but look at how hard this person has it, at least it's not you" bullshit that is so fucking toxic and just adds more trauma and shame on top of what you're already feeling.

We need to start ebbing and flowing together instead of being forced into the ebbs and flows that capitalism and patriarchy demand/allow us to be in. We cannot pay away our grief. We cannot pay away our love of people who have transitioned to the Otherworld. It is impossible.

Normalize discussing death. Normalize sharing what ritual or practices worked for you with your own grief. Share your stories. Sit with them. Allow empathy to knock you on your ass for more than one minute. It will be okay. Breathe from your stomach, not from your aching heart.

To literally PAY away the pain. And as our capitalist society continues to fail and collapse, we are faced with such an incredibly high amount of death that money literally cannot fix, because we're realizing we don't have any fucking money OR a community to help us through.

But death? Grief? Loss? As regular ppl, we need to be able to discuss this w/ each other, feel empathy, give suggestions, share stories, etc. It's our RIGHT as humans to have control and ritual around death. Yet, we have been conditioned otherwise- to fear this part of ourselves

There are a lot of mental health disorders that require medical/therapeutic attention, ABSOLUTELY. My ADHD/PMDD is one of them. I can't go to my mother or aunt and ask them to send in a script for my Adderall. And nor should I be able to.

I'm not saying therapy HASN'T supported this type of trauma- obviously it has. But it is difficult and expensive as fuck to find it. And look at how capitalism and patriarchy has taken away community care and forced us to have to PAY for the support we need. It's so fucked!

If we lived in a society that actually honored and acknowledged Death, if we could talk about it when we started struggling with a wave of grief- we wouldn't be forced to spend money we don't have on therapy that isn't equipped to support these issues.

I felt so isolated and alone. I couldn't talk to friends and family because they were too sad/unable/unwilling to listen to me, and even therapists couldn't be bothered. Luckily my ADHD diagnosis helped with handling my grief but JFC it was a constant letdown.

But when I first started reaching out to therapists, I COULDN'T FIND ONE. They were either booked, busy, or legitimately told me they couldn't help with my child loss. And I knew why- because it was too fucking sad, and hit too close to home as ppl with uteri.

Ppl couldn't handle the fact that this was my pregnancy story, that this loss actually happened the way it did, and I didn't have other children to soften the blow. So I was like, let me go to therapy now. And I did. And it was good for some things, absolutely. I got my ADHD dx.

I was on UI at the end of my pregnancy so when I went in after my labor, the dude asked me what jobs I planned on doing and I burst into tears and said I had planned on working from home and being a mother. He froze and then asked hopefully "but you have other kids, right?"

I reached went to groups and I could feel the energy being sucked out of the room when I shared my story. Not only had my child died, but they were (and still are) my only child. That one fact was too much. If I had another kid, well, at least what, I have a backup? For real.

There was no compassion, just a checklist. Just a reminder to reach out to a therapist when I'm ready, here's a list of support groups, have a nice day. And looking back, armed with the knowledge and journey I've been on, it was a trauma on top of the Big Trauma.

He asked me cold questions, if I had ideations, if I wanted to die. And I was like, hello. Do you see where I am? What has happened to me? What I have lost? I'm saying this less than 24 hrs after I came out of the surgery that removed my dead child from my body.

But when I lost my kid, I was in a hospital room, cut open from an emergency c-section, crying that I wish I died instead of my kid. Which, I'm sorry, is a NORMAL THING FOR A PARENT TO SAY. And so they sent for a psych eval, and a young man who was in training arrived.

Now, I can understand my parents' position, & their parents. A lot of the issues my family as a whole need(ed) to work on was the trauma of British colonization & Catholic Church abuses. There were no tools for that, and thus intergenerational trauma is a major thing I work on.

When I was growing up, therapy was used as a threat or a silencing tool- if I or my bros were too upset, freaking out, whatever it was, we'd be told we'll be sent to therapy. When we left the house, and expressed emotions, we were told "just go to therapy!" There was no inbetween

Therapy is an important tool to have access to. It should be affordable, easily accessible, and is absolutely something that has helped so many of us. However. There is only so much it can do in our current state. Especially with death, in any form.

In keeping with my tweets this morning, I want to say I've been thinking a lot about therapy and how it seen as this "other" that will replace what community care (and this includes your families, however they are defined) can provide for so many of us.

The majority of our rituals are based around capitalism. Fuck that noise. You don't need to wait for an expensive funeral or retreat to have a ritual for your loss or trauma. You don't need to "wait for the right time" or pretend that you're okay. Reclaim your right to ritual.

Speaking of trauma, of death, of loss, and of the fear of all of this is a subversive act. It is one of the many ways to bring capitalism and patriarchy to its knees. I'm not talking about trauma dumping but about the actual ritual surrounding these events.

They'll sell you life insurance, telling you not to leave your family unable to afford the life they make so expensive to live. They tell you to make sure to have your affairs in order so your family isn't stuck with a bill. Money. Capital, even in death. What the actual fuck.

Our capitalist society wants to extract money from EVERYTHING. They do not actually care about LIFE, they want whatever wealth that life may have had and they want it for themselves. They'll extend your life to keep extracting money from you and your families.

I don't know how to end this stream of consciousness. I just wish we collectively could have actual relief. Real relief. That actually makes foundational differences in our lives, in our minds, in our health, in our security and stability.

If I had money, my hands might heal. If my hands healed, I could work, I could find meaningful work. I would be happy. But right now, it's very, very difficult to pull through all of this. Just so much piled on to so much. But I guess all I can do is just try.

If I could pay off this debt, fix my house, have health insurance, have consistent therapy, have the means to do the work that helps me heal, not have to wake up each day in a panic about what new financial hell I may find myself in, then I think happiness would be a side effect.

One of the biggest lies capitalism tells us is that money can't buy happiness. These stupid fucking proverbs and saying and parables telling us poor fuckers to just remember money isn't everything! Can't buy happiness! Yes it fucking can. It absolutely can.

I'm feeling emotionally hungover today. My face hurts from hysterically crying for hours yesterday. My chest hurts from the hours of hyperventilation and panic attacks. I feel so much shame and embarrassment for my behavior. And I cannot shake the fact that money would help.

And that my child loss, the loss of so many loved ones, the issues with my brother, my own issues, these were all proof that I am being punished and that I deserve to be punished because I fucked up this credit card thing. That's the trauma of capitalism.

I truly felt like, I just don't deserve help. I can't even help myself. How can I ever expect to care for a child if I can't even take care of a credit card. That was the one thought I couldn't shake. I really believe that I failed to "care for" a credit card.

The blue collar Irish Catholic in me hates that I'm listing all of this. I know people have it so much worse. But I'm also a HSP, empath, witch. I internalize so much. I have gone my whole life caring for and carrying so much for others. Yesterday, my CPTSD/PTSD went haywire.

I worked corporate 9-5 from 22-33, undiagnosed with ADHD, working a bartending gig on the side the whole time. I had to pay rent, car insurance, while being expected to pay $900/mo in student loans on a $35/k starting salary.

What the fuck are we actually supposed to do? I've worked almost every day of my life since I was 14. I literally had three jobs in high school, while playing 3 varsity sports. I worked all through college, while needing private loans to finance it.

We work hard. We do what we can, with what we have, going through all we have gone through. But every day retraumatizes me. From the lack of giving a shit about COVID, lack of universal healthcare, lack of debt relief, student and otherwise, lack of UI, lack of stability-

I received a letter a week later that basically said, since you aren't a mother with a living child, you no longer qualify for Medicaid low-income insurance. So it's just trauma on top of trauma, it feels so neverending.

Medicaid and United Healthcare, neither one willing to just fucking delete him for me. No one understanding what I was saying, that my child DIED and I cannot get these calls any longer. And when they finally removed him, they removed my insurance too.

I lost my health insurance because Medicaid/United Healthcare wouldn't stop robocalling me to remind me to get my child's checkups and booster shots, at least once a week receiving voicemails telling me to care for my dead child. I had to call screaming, back and forth between

But it's not only money, not really.  There was a post I retweeted a while ago that was like, there's not one problem I have that can't be solved with money. And it's so fucking true. I can't afford therapy any longer. I'm off some of my meds for $ reasons and health reasons.

And now here I am, with a bill that I feel may finally destroy me, if not for my sweet husband insisting that we will be okay, that he will be able to pick up extra work soon, that I will be able to find remote work for sure, that we will make it work. It's only money, right?

And then Sept 5, 2021 rolls around, and @JoeBiden and @TheDemocrats allow UI benefits to end. Because of COVID, my dog sitting business decreased at least 70%, and by the time UI ran out, I barely had anything, and it was all off the books, bc my clients understood.

So now I have a physical ailment caused by grief and pain and loss and stress and I am still dealing with it to this day. I used to be able to pick up extra work as a bartender- I couldn't do that anymore, not with open sores on my hands. So I relied on UI.

It blisters and breaks and forms weeping wounds that cripple your hands. It's auto-immune and my Irish family has had every type of auto-immune disorder you can think of. I immediately think of my grandmother, with RA that effectively disabled her feet and hands.

I'll never forget the phone call with my father, delivering the news gently but also in disbelief, and how I felt a burst in my hands. This energy burst that turns into dyshidrotic eczema, all over my hands and right foot. It feels like a sunburn under your skin.

We saw him last in December 2019, at a Christmas dinner, he had just finished a round of chemo for lung cancer. And for the rest of his life, we couldn't see him bc we couldn't risk getting him more sick. And when I found out the cancer spread to his brain, my body broke.

They die. My brother goes into crisis. We finally get him into a rehab. And in August 2020, we get the news that my most beloved uncle, at the age of 59, now has cancer that has spread to his brain, and only has a few months to live. And we can't see him, because of COVID.

I went to therapy. I went on meds. I find out I have ADHD first through a fucking Twitter thread. I finally get diagnosed. Things are going fairly well. We start feeling slightly stable. And then, COVID. And my FIL immediately gets it. And then my uncle.

And through ADHD masking I managed to make it through my 20s, but then at 33 my child dies in labor at 40 wks after a perfectly healthy pregnancy. I have an emergency C-section. And that trauma, and grief, and unimaginable loss made me lose all capacity to mask.

I know that capitalism is set up to do this to me. I'm supposed to feel this way. I'm supposed to blame myself for my failures, and I'm supposed to have my life ruined because I wasn't born with money, I dared to get a degree, and then my brain couldn't manage certain tasks.

Another huge financial mistake that I've made- I graduated with a BA in 2008, and I struggled with my loans, and defaulted on some of them, and for my whole life my financial situation is such a source of overwhelming shame. It shuts down my system and I feel like a burden.

I called my two best friends, hysterical. I knew my husband would be understanding- he's not good with money either, he shares blame in this, and would never put it on me or scream or anything, he's an angel truly- but I had no compassion for myself. It was just another failure.

So we paid the minimum on this card, just trying to stay afloat, and then in May 2020 I'm lucky to get unemployment, I pay it off right away, or so I think, and now here I am in Dec 2021 realizing that not only did I not pay it off, but now a summons is at my house.

Our whole kitchen backed up and flooded with muddy water (thankfully not waste water). An 80 year old tree's root pushed up too far and burst this pipe in this old farmhouse. And so, our wedding gift money went to the car issue and pipe issue, and then taxes were due.

We were going to use money from our wedding to pay the card off, but two weeks before our wedding we had to get a new car, our old one finally kicked it. And three days before our wedding, which was at the home my husband inherited (a true blessing, I know), a pipe burst.

We got that credit card to pay for my wedding ring. We were given my grandmother's and my husband's grandmothers rings and we blended it all together, as cheaply as possible. And I couldn't stop thinking, you don't deserve this ring, look at what it's done to you.

My great-grandmother and grandmother were both committed/in rehab, so maybe it's just finally my turn, and it's a fucking credit card bill that finally did me in. It's really hard to use mindfulness when you just go crashing down so far, into such a dark place, unable to focus.

Why does my brain work against me like this? Why am I 37 and still struggling so much with money? Why do I have to have this much grief, and loss, and trauma, and stress, and why isn't therapy and breathing and grounding and all that shit ever enough?

So yesterday I just fully breakdown. Like, can't breathe, hysterical, calling the crisis hotline, just thinking- it would be better if I commit myself. I'm ruining my husband's life. How could I miss this payment issue? How could I remember it after what was happening then?

So I pay the credit card, at the very least, right? Cut to yesterday, where it turns out I actually didn't because the time the payment actually came out, my checking acct no longer had the money in it, because I was paying for so much of my brother's stuff, running on fumes, etc

This is also all on top of the loss of my only child in labor at 40 wks in 2017, getting my ADHD diagnosis a year later, and still working through my sexual assault- assaulted by a friend's husband a week after their wedding, on their couch, as I slept. It is just so much.

I was reeling and running on fumes. My FIL and uncle both died from COVID in April and May. We had to help clean up a lot of my FIL papers and finances and it was just A. LOT. And during all of that my brother was just not. well, and in grave danger of dying.

He was starving himself while also being brainwashed by a woman he met when he lived in TX. It sounds absurd but it was the truth- from Feb-June 2020, my brother wasn't well and we couldn't get him to understand he needed help. And May 2020 was the worst of it.

At the time of this payment, I was actively trying to get my brother off the streets and into a rehab or psych ward. He was in a mental health crisis, living out of his car, wandering the streets barefoot, getting into fights, and claiming he was the Kalki.

So I get a fairly good chunk of money, enough to pay off the $3,100 the credit card was at, I did this on May 18, 2020- the same day the $ hit my act. And with ADHD and executive dysfunction, it's like, once you manage to do it, it's done. You don't give a fuck anymore.

I absolutely broke down. I swore that I paid this credit card bill off last year, because I was approved for unemployment (I work for myself as a dog/pet sitter, and thankfully NYS gave unemployment to animal care workers) and I received back payments for unemployment.

A long thread on how ADHD, executive dysfunction, PTSD/CPTSD, grief, COVID, and sexual assault all meet together to create a chaotic, draining, triggering day for me. 

Yesterday, we were served a summons to collect a debt on a credit card with a $4,500 balance.
